# Basic Sorting Algos

- Each sorting algo uses swap to swap two item


Algo:           Minimum     Sequential  Bubble (smarter)    Insertion

Best Case:      O(n)        O(1)        O(n)                O(n)

Worst Case:     O(n)        O(n)        O(n^2)              O(n^2)

Average Case:   O(n)        O(n)        O(n^2)              O(n^2)

Description:
    Minimum
        - Unless list is sorted, you always have to traverse the whole list to ensure you found the min

    Sequential
        - You can stop the second you find the item
        - BC: Item at first pos
        - WC: Item at last pos
        - AC: (1 + 2 + .... n) / n (average) = (n+1)/2 = O(n)

    Bubble
        - You can stop when the list is sorted
        - BC: List is already sorted
        - WC: Every item in wrong place
        - AC: Closer to O(n^2) then to O(n)

    Insertion
        - BC: List already sorted
        




## Selection Sort

- Steps: 
    1. Search the entire list of the position of the smallest item
    2. If position not equal to first position
        - Swap the items at those positions

    3. Algo returns to second position and repeats this process
        - Swapping the smallest item wit hthe item at the second position if necessary

    4. Each loop, start at c+1 where c is previous start position

    5. When algo reaches last position, list is sorted


    Unsorted:       5   3   1   2   4
    After pass 1:   1*  3   5*  2   4
    After pass 2:   1   2*  5   3*  4
    After pass 3:   1   2   3*  5*  4
    After pass 4:   1   2   3   4*  5*


- Complexity O(n^2)
    - Repeats outer loop  n-1 times
    - on first pass inner loop executes n-1 times
    - on second outer loop, inner loop executes n-2 times
    - on last outer loop, inner loop executes just once
    - (n-1) + (n-2) + ... + 1 = n(n-1) / 2 = (1/2)n^2 - (1/2) n 


## Bubble Sort
- Steps
    1. Start at the beginning of the list
    
    2. Compare pairs of data items as it moves down to the end

    3. Each time the items in the pair are out of order
        - Swap them

        - has effect of bubbling largest items to the end of the list

    4. Repeat the process from the beginning of the list
        - go the to next-to-last item

    5. Repeat until it begins with the last item

        Unsorted List:      5   4   2   1   3 
    PASS 1: (n-1)
    Compare 5 and 4
        1st Comparison:     4*  5*  2   1   3 
    Compare 5 and 2
        2nd Comparison:     4   2*  5*  1   3
    Compare 5 and 1         
        3rd Comparison:     4   2   1*  5*  3
    Compare 5 and 3
        4th Comparison:     4   2   1   3*  5*

    PASS 2: (n-2)
    Compare 4 and 2
        1st Comparison:     2*  4*  1   3   5
    Compare 4 and 1
        2nd Comparison:     2   1*  4*  3   5
    Compare 4 and 3 
        3rd Comparison:     2   1   3*  4*  5
    
    PASS 3: (n-3)
    Compare 2 and 1
        1st Comparison:     1*  2*  3   4   5
    Compare 2 and 3
        2nd Comparison:     1   2   3   4   5

    Pass 4 (n-4):
    Compare 1 and 2:
        1st Comparison:     1   2   3   4   5

    DONE!

- Complexity: O(n^2)
    - 2 loops
        - (1/2)n^2 - (1/2)n
    - won't preform swap if list is already sorted
    - worst-case: greater than linear (every additional item will usually be compared with all other items, maybe multiple times, MY GUESS)

Notes
- Can make minor adjustment to improve best-case to linear
    - If no swap occured during pass through the main loop, then list is sorted (bubble_sort_with_tweak)

## Insertion Sort
    - Attempts to exploit the partial ordering of the list

- Steps: 
    1. On the ith pass through the list
        - where i ranges from 1 to n-1
        - the ith item should be inserted into its proper place among the first i items in the list
    2. After the ith pass
        - the first i tiems should be in sorted order

    - Basically, take the first i-1 cards
        - then take the card i and find its proper place in the first i cards
        - ex: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q1JdRUh1_98 
        

        Unsorted List:  2   5   1   4   3

    Pass 1 (where to insert 5 in i-1):
        i-1:            2   
        i:                  5
        Comparison 1:   2   5

    Pass 2 (where to insert 1 in i-1):
        i-1:            2   5
        i:                      1
        Comparison 1:   2   1*  5*
        Comparison 2:   1*  2*  5

    Pass 3 (Where to insert 4 in i-1):
        i-1:            1   2   5
        i:                          4
        Comparison 1:   1   2   4*  5*
        Comparison 2:   1   2   4   5
        ---- Break since no swap made
    
    Pass 4 (Where to insert 3 in i-1):
        i-1:            1   2   4   5
        i:                              3
        Comparison 1:   1   2   4   3*  5*
        Comparison 2:   1   2   3*  4*  5
        Comparison 3:   1   2   3   4   5
        ---- Break since no swap made
    


- Complexity
    - O(n^2)
    - 2 loops
        - out loop traverses the positions from 1 to n-1
            * For each position i in this loop, you save the item and start the inner loop at position i - 1
        
            * For each position j in this loop, you move the item to position j+1 until you find the insertion point for the saved ith item.
    


    
    
